Then read 'From the Ashes of Angels&quot;.  It links ancient 'fables' to each other.  <br>
<br>
 I feel that the Old Testament speaks of real events.  It seems fragmented, since it's been edited/censored over the years.  There are something like 80 different 'religions' in the world, 60 of which are not contiguous, yet they all have accounts of a flood.  <br>
<br>
Also, there is Hapgood's earth crust dispacement theory.  It speaks of the crust of the earth moving geologically 'sudden' as much as 10 degrees.  This would cause polar meltdowns and cause a global flood. <br>
<br>
I think that there is much truth in Gilgamesh.  Daniel, the prophet was captured by the Babylonians and kept as a prophet, and eventually was given governership over a province.  Many of the biblical accounts are thought to have been introduced by Daniel as a result of his capture.  That's not to say that there aren't literal truths to the old testament.  It just means that many cultures knew of the truth.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>. Apart from the fact that there is absolutely no evidence anywhere of a global flood at any point in human history<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Again, I respectfully disagree.  There has been a submerged city found off of the coast of India, there is another one being explored off of the coast of cuba, there is another one off of the coast of japan.  Marine archeology is in its infancy but these amazing discoveries have been made.  Here are some examples.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/south_asia/1923794.stm">news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/south_asia/1923794.stm</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.indolink.com/Religion/r091702-130924.php">www.indolink.com/Religion/r091702-130924.php</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
I'd like to close by saying that perhaps conventional archeology has not found evidence of ancient global flooding, but I contend that they are looking at terrestrial examples.  Graham Hancock has written a wonderful book called 'Underworld' that explores lost underwater civilizations, that may well be the smoking gun of Noah's flood....<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub16.ezboard.com/bunexplainedmysteries.showUserPublicProfile?gid=towelfrood7>towelfrood7</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 91<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/9/03 9:41:15 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Genesis</span><hr size=1> Chargerfan,<br>
<br>
Just a couple of thoughts in reply to your previous post…<br>
<br>
Firstly, you say that the justification for the Biblical Flood was the behaviour of the Nephilim (interbreeding with humans, etc).. do you believe the purpose of the Flood was to <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>destroy</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> the Nephilim then?<br>
<br>
If so, surely it failed … since the Bible mentions the Nephilim being around still along time <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>after</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> the Flood: I can’t recall the exact verse, but Moses &amp; the Israelities bump into them during their wanderings in the desert &amp; decide to leave them alone, on account of their being “Giants among men” or something similar?<br>
<br>
Anyway Vis~a~vis “the Flood”,  there are many examples of <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>localised</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> (not global) flooding around the world, throughout history, that’s obviously true… however I don’t know of ANY evidence anywhere of a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>global</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> flood, of the sort supposedly described in Genesis &amp; other ancient mythologies.<br>
<br>
The sites you linked to (about Indian flooding &amp; mythologies) were really interesting (thanks for those! <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/image/emoticons_classic/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> )…. I agree that religious/ belief systems sometimes describe actual events (or versions of them) ~ arguably you could say the point of belief systems is to help people make sense of life/ the world around them, so they will include descriptions &amp; interpretations (however flawed or slanted, for instance toward one particular people in the case of the Israelites of the Old Testament) of important events, such as floods, famines, wars etc.<br>
<br>
By way of maybe illustrating this, the following is from www.ancientrade.com/chad/...lood2.html ~ re. Origin of middle eastern flood myths etc..<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>THE FLOOD THEORY<br>
At first, the rising Atlantic brought the Mediterranean all the way up to the edge the Bosphorus Valley, right near the Black Lake, but was held back by a 400 foot tall dam, only 2 miles wide. (I say &quot;only&quot; because this dam had the weight of the entire world's oceans bearing down on it.) Then about 7,600 years ago, the dam burst. Saltwater roared into the Black Lake with 200 times the force of Niagra Falls. That means over 10 cubic miles of saltwater (about the volume of Lake Mead, Nevada) rocketing through the Bosphorus valve every day, spurting flumes as fast as 50 mph.<br>
<br>
… it turns out that this Flood Theory has compelling human relevance. It just so happens that modern man migrated out of Africa 100,000 years ago and began to settle Mesopotamia about 15,000 years ago. Almost certainly there were many cultures living around the Black Sea 7,600 years ago. So we're not just talking about an enormous, anonymous geologic event: we're talking about one of the most enormous natural disasters in human history. Many people would've been witness and, sadly, victim to such a catastrophe.<br>
<br>
The Bosphorus flooding wouldn't have just been a &quot;really bad month&quot;: it was part of a geological process that took the better part of 10,000 years to get started (in order for enough ice to melt to get the Mediterranean high enough to punch through the Bosphorus). Even during the flood, Ryan &amp; Pitman calculate that the shores of the Black Sea would've risen about 6-12 inches a day (which is still incredible when you think about it). Furthermore, it is thought that hundreds of years passed before water levels stopped rising.<br>
<br>
This discussion is not to imply it was a happy time on the shores of the drowning Black Lake. Freshwater fish were dying from the salt, crops were being wrecked, water was getting contaminated and people were getting the heck out of dodge. Pitman calculated that, even if you lived at the far north end of the Black Lake, when the Bosphorus broke in the south you would have had to flee the rising shores by a quarter-mile per day -- up to a mile per day if you lived in a river valley where the land is flatter. Villages would've been washed through in weeks (quick enough that we may still find remains today, but not fast enough to be literally swept away in a flash). So we are still not talking about people across the Black Sea running away from tidal waves.<br>
<br>
The scene at the Bosphorus itself would've been, indeed, quite dramatic, but hardly global or sudden. The build-up of water took generations (actually millenia). Given that timeframe, even the Hollywood bursting of the dam would've been preceded by seismic rumblings long before the dreadful moment, which we'd like to think would've compelled prehistoric man to high-tail his prehistoric behind to higher ground. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
..point being, these were very real but LOCALISED .. not global events.. they'd have seemed to take in the 'whole world' to the people affected by them, because they simply had no knowledge of a world beyond their own region .. which is why  the Bible curiously claims that there is a high mountain from which all the kingdoms of the world can be seen. (~ which also ofcourse implies a flat earth):<br>
